@lynncyrin I've renamed the issue here because I *think* that your use case is mostly about a truncated *string* representation, is that right?

I don't think it would be a good idea to just have `relativedelta.shortened()` because the semantics of that are somewhat unclear. `relativedelta`, unfortunately, is a chimera class that is a mixture of "partial dates" and "calendar deltas", see #449 (refactoring out `partialdatetime`) and #524 (refactoring out `calendardelta`), and so there's no clear hierarchical ordering that can be foreshortened in an obvious way.

For the string-representation question, I think the way forward is to implement `__format__` on `relativedelta`, and come up with a format-specification mini-DSL to specify components (I guess [PEP 3101](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-3101/) is the best documentation I can find for this). This has some of the problems inherent in issue #444 (no existing standard), and we'll probably want to get those two formatting mini-specs to at least *partially* agree.

We may want to see what [pandas' offsets](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/timeseries.html#dateoffset-objects) are doing and if they have any formatting tips. That said when making trade-offs between being useful and being correct, `pandas` tends to choose useful and `dateutil` tends to choose "correct" (in the abstract), so it may be that the philosophies don't mesh. @jbrockmendel  Any thoughts?

@lynncyrin I'd totally welcome a contribution, but I will warn you that unfortunately I've been at least partially paralyzed with indecision about formatting specs lately (see #444 and #454), so it might not be an amazingly fun contribution to make (since it is mostly about digging up standards and making the case for them, and trying to harmonize various representations - and likely it will be a while before anything gets merged).

