Hi all, I am facing a related issue but in the case of using `shared_ptr` instead of `unique_ptr`. Here is a minimal example:

```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

class Foo : public std::enable_shared_from_this<Foo> {
    Foo() = default;
    ~Foo() = default;

public:
    static std::shared_ptr<Foo> create() {
        struct A : std::allocator<Foo> {
            void construct(void* p) { ::new(p) Foo(); }
            void destroy(Foo* p) { p->~Foo(); }
        };
        return std::allocate_shared<Foo>(A());
    }
};

PYBIND11_MODULE(foo, m) {
    pybind11::class_<Foo, std::shared_ptr<Foo>>(m, "Foo")
        .def(pybind11::init(&Foo::create));
}
```
The intent is to enforce instances of `Foo` to be managed by `shared_ptr` (hence the private constructor/destructor + factory method), making it always safe to call `shared_from_this()`. The use of `std::allocate_shared` is only [one of the possible methods](https://stackoverflow.com/a/11344174/1951907) to give `shared_ptr` access to the otherwise inaccessible constructor/destructor, but I believe all other methods involving a protected/private destructor would also fail when wrapped with pybind11 with the same errors.

