Yeah, that's right. We could comment out the original directive with a note saying "duplicated in <include file location>."On May 1, 2017 6:37 PM, Brad Warren <notifications@github.com> wrote:I want to do some more testing here but after playing with this for a bit, it appears whether or not Nginx errors out if there a duplicate directive depends on the directive. This is fine:
ssl_session_cache shared:le_nginx_SSL:1m;
ssl_session_cache shared:le_nginx_SSL:1m;

but this is not:
ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;
ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;

This is an unfortunate side effect of using include because previously we just wouldn't include the directive if an identical one was already present. This means that switching to this approach will cause Certbot to fail for configurations where it previously worked.
